er'd</HI>; and so <HI>Paul, who laboured abundantly</HI> in preaching the <HI>Gospell,</HI> sayes <HI>this work</HI> was the <HI>grace</HI> which was <HI>given</HI> him by <HI>Christ in him,</HI> by which <HI>grace</HI> also he was, what ere he was, that was worth any thing, having nothing but what he had <HI>received,</HI> that made him <HI>differ from another</HI>; by which <HI>grace</HI> or <HI>gift</HI> all <HI>boasting</HI> and <HI>glorying in selfe</HI> was continually <HI>excluded,</HI> and the glory of all to be given still to <HI>God,</HI> and not <HI>flesh, man,</HI> and <HI>selfe</HI>: so that while <HI>Iudas</HI> could blame none but
